    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-05-10T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-05-10T11:00:00-05:00" n="338"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d338">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 658.119/360</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-05-10T17:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 10</hi> [<hi rend="italic">11</hi>], <hi
                                rend="italic">1918, 5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received May 11, 7.17 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>10002. War Trade Board [from <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1"
                        >Sheldon</persName>]:</p>
                <p>No. 561. Referring my 440, Embassy’s 9558, April 18, 10 a.m., and especially my
                    544, May 9.<note n="6" xml:id="d338fn6">Neither printed.</note>
                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_CG1">Carlsson</persName> informs me that
                    the steamships <pb facs="0393" n="1227" xml:id="pg_1227"/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Stockholm, Axel Johnson, Prinsessan Ingeborg</hi> and <hi
                        rend="italic">Pedro Christophersen</hi> are ready to leave Sweden for
                    loading cereals in the Plate. Owners would like to have option on the outward
                    voyage (<hi rend="italic">a</hi>) to go direct from Sweden to the Plate or (<hi
                        rend="italic">b</hi>) call at Hampton Roads for bunkers, in which case they
                    would take coal or general cargoes depending on speed with which loading could
                    be accomplished, to approved consignees at the Plate. On the return trip they
                    would call at United States port and wait for signing of general agreement,
                    failing which the grain should be sold at cost to the United States Government
                    if the agreement be not signed by July 15 and thereupon bunkers be furnished to
                    the boats and they be allowed to return forthwith to Sweden provided that they
                    were not playing the rôle of replacing boats for Swedish boats which, had been
                    in the United States and allowed in exchange to return to Sweden. While I feel I
                    have in general your authority to agree to this, please cable your approval
                    immediately.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
